comments.text:
I have to say that it's true, but I have the feeling that a lot of the features they ship are half-baked. 

E.g. the agent teams was pretty broken when they released, the remote sessions worked half of the time for me, channels release is unclear and have a ton of doc gaps that need "reverse engineering".

On the other hand, I think it's a great example of shipping like crazy power using AI to the extreme. But, as always, it comes with tradeoffs:

- Documentation is almost always outdated or half-baked;
- Cognitive load of users is extreme: you could not even start testing A when they release B;
- Software is still buggy (that's a fact for anyone using claude code), and features outrun core improvements;
- Getting support (on X) is almost impossible: probably they have their own cognitive load broken.

Let's see how it goes in the future, but my hot take is that they need to find a way to stabilize somehow "what" they even offer. Claude Code, Web, Schedules, CoWork, etc.
